## Grammar

- Review and repetition of nominal clauses for descriptions (“X is Y”, e.g., אֱלֹהִים טוֹב)
- Extensive practice: perfect and participle forms for simple past/present states (e.g., אָהֵב, סוֹלֵחַ, שָׂמֵחַ)
- Simple presentative use (“קוֹל אוֹמֵר”, “כֻּלָּם שָׁמֵחַ”)
- Use of כְּמוֹ ("like/as") for simple comparisons in context (“כְּמוֹ כּוֹכָב”)
- Abstract noun usage: אַהֲבָה, סְלִיחָה, שְׂמֵחָה, שָׁלוֹם
- Explicit repetition of previously learned verbs in narrative and speech contexts
- Simple, direct Qal forms (mainly perfect and participle)
- Repetition of opposites (טוֹב/רַע, גָּדוֹל/קָטָן, שָׂמֵחַ/עָצוּב) for reinforcement
- Practice with all/each/every (הַכֹּל, כֻּלָּם) and equality (שָׁוִים)
- Review: past, present, and simple future tenses (with minimal explicit future, using context only)
